{{Infobox news event | image = | caption = | date = Thursday, {{start date|2003|4|24}} | time = | place = [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], Canada |coordinates = | casualties1 = '''Fatalities:''' 7 | casualties2 = '''Injured:''' 4 | notes= }}
The '''2003 Etobicoke gas explosion''' was a disaster which occurred on April 24, 2003, after a backhoe operated by [[Enbridge]] contractor Precision breached a pipeline on Bloor Street in the [[Etobicoke]] district of [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]]. The resulting explosion destroyed a nearby two-story mixed commercial and residential building killing seven persons and injured another four. Enbridge and several other companies were fined for the disaster in 2011.<ref>[http://news.nationalpost.com/2011/12/16/enbridge-gas-fined-in-deadly-etobicoke-explosion/]</ref> The explosion was the worst pipeline disaster in Canada since the [[LaSalle Heights Disaster]] in 1965. A memorial garden was dedicated at the site of the explosion in 2008.<ref>[http://www.insidetoronto.com/news-story/20446-etobicoke-memorial-garden-honours-seven-lost-in-explosion/]</ref>
