[[he:קרייזלר טאון אנד קאנטרי]]

An '''edge-localized mode''' (“ELM”) is a disruptive [[instability]] occurring in the edge region of a [[tokamak]] [[plasma (physics)|plasma]] due to the quasi-periodic relaxation of a transport barrier{{clarify|date=December 2015}} previously formed during an {{nobr|L → H}} transition (i.e., in {{nobr|[[high-confinement mode|H-mode]]).}} This phenomenon was first observed in the [[ASDEX Upgrade|ASDEX tokamak]] in 1981.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=F.|first=Wagner,|last2=A.R.|first2=Field,|last3=G.|first3=Fussmann,|last4=J.V.|first4=Hofmann,|last5=M.E.|first5=Manso,|last6=O.|first6=Vollmer,|last7=José|first7=Matias,|date=1990|title=Recent results of H-mode studies on ASDEX|journal=13th International Conference on Plasma Physics and Controlled Nuclear Fusion|volume=|pages=|hdl=10198/9098}}</ref>
The development of edge-localized modes poses a major challenge in [[Magnetic confinement fusion|magnetic fusion]] research with tokamaks, as these instabilities can damage wall components (in particular [[divertor]] plates) by ablating them away due to their extremely high energy transfer rate (GW/m<sup>2</sup>).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://arstechnica.com/science/2018/09/a-third-dimension-helps-tokamak-fusion-reactor-avoid-wall-destroying-instability/|title=A third dimension helps Tokamak fusion reactor avoid wall-destroying instability|last=Lee|first=Chris|date=13 Sep 2018|work=Ars Technica|access-date=2018-09-17|language=en-us}}</ref>
==Simulation and modeling== In 2006 an initiative (called Project Aster) was started to simulate a full ELM cycle including its onset, the highly non-linear phase, and its decay. However, this did not constitute a “true” ELM cycle, since a true ELM cycle would require modeling the slow growth after the crash, in order to have a second ELM. In 2015, results of the first simulation to demonstrate repeated ELM cycling was published.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Orain|first=François|last2=Bécoulet|first2=M|last3=Morales|first3=J|last4=Huijsmans|first4=G T A|last5=Dif-Pradalier|first5=G|last6=Hoelzl|first6=M|last7=Garbet|first7=X|last8=Pamela|first8=S|last9=Nardon|first9=E|date=2014-11-28|title=Non-linear MHD modeling of edge localized mode cycles and mitigation by resonant magnetic perturbations|journal=Plasma Physics and Controlled Fusion|volume=57|issue=1|pages=014020|doi=10.1088/0741-3335/57/1/014020|issn=0741-3335}}</ref> A key element to obtaining repeated relaxations was to include diamagnetic effects in the model equations. Diamagnetic effects have also been shown to expand the size of the parameter space in which solutions of repeated [[Tokamak sawtooth|sawteeth]] can be recovered compared to a resistive MHD model.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Halpern|first=F D|last2=Leblond|first2=D|last3=Lütjens|first3=H|last4=Luciani|first4=J-F|date=2010-11-30|title=Oscillation regimes of the internal kink mode in tokamak plasmas|journal=Plasma Physics and Controlled Fusion|volume=53|issue=1|pages=015011|doi=10.1088/0741-3335/53/1/015011|issn=0741-3335}}</ref>
==Prevention and control== Research involving prevention of edge localized mode formation is underway. A paper was recently published that suggested a novel method of countering this phenomenon by injecting static magnetic noisy energy into the containment field as a containment-stabilization regime; this may decrease ELM amplitude.{{cn|date=March 2018}} [[ASDEX Upgrade]] has had some success using pellet injection to increase the frequency and thereby decrease the severity of ELM bursts.{{cn|date=March 2018}}
==Control in practice== As of late 2011, several research facilities have demonstrated active control or suppression of ELMs in tokamak plasmas. For example, the [[KSTAR|KSTAR tokamak]] uses specific asymmetric three-dimensional magnetic field configurations to achieve this goal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iter.org/newsline/198/950|title=KSTAR announces successful ELM suppression|author=Kwon, Eunhee|date=2011-11-10|accessdate=2011-12-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Park|first=Jong-Kyu|last2=Jeon|first2=YoungMu|last3=In|first3=Yongkyoon|last4=Ahn|first4=Joon-Wook|last5=Nazikian|first5=Raffi|last6=Park|first6=Gunyoung|last7=Kim|first7=Jaehyun|last8=Lee|first8=HyungHo|last9=Ko|first9=WonHa|first10=Hyun-Seok|last10=Kim|first11=Nikolas C.|last11=Logan|first12=Zhirui|last12=Wang|first13=Eliot A.|last13=Feibush|first14=Jonathan E.|last14=Menard|first15=Michael C.|last15=Zarnstroff|date=2018-09-10|title=3D field phase-space control in tokamak plasmas|journal=Nature Physics|language=En|doi=10.1038/s41567-018-0268-8|issn=1745-2473}}</ref>
==See also== * [[Resonant magnetic perturbations]], used to control ELMs * [[Plasma instability]] * [[Tokamak]]
