'''Himpunan Hijau''' (English: "Green Assembly") is a Malaysian environmentalist movement protesting against the Lynas Advanced Materials Plant (LAMP), a rare earth processing plant operating in [[Gebeng]], [[Kuantan]], [[Pahang]] set up by the [[Australian]] company [[Lynas]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=SPYKERMAN|first1=NEVILLE|title=Himpunan Hijau involves international NGOs in its anti-Lynas campaigns|url=http://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2013/08/24/himpunan-hijau-involves-international-ngos-in-antilynas-campaigns/|publisher=The Star|accessdate=17 June 2016|date=24 August 2013}}</ref><ref name="MI 20140902">{{cite web|last1=Ng|first1=Eileen|title=Lynas gets full operating licence before TOL expiry date|url=http://www.themalaysianinsider.com/malaysia/article/lynas-gets-full-operating-licence-before-tol-expiry-date|publisher=The [[Malaysian Insider]]|accessdate=3 September 2014|date=2 September 2014|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140904034335/http://www.themalaysianinsider.com/malaysia/article/lynas-gets-full-operating-licence-before-tol-expiry-date|archivedate=4 September 2014|df=}}</ref> The refinery process is accused of dumping tonnes of toxic and radioactive waste on the local lives, livelihoods, the environment and the health of future generations.<ref>{{citeweb| url=http://stoplynas.org/tag/himpunan-hijau/ | agency=Stop Lynas | title=About Stop Lynas | accessdate=17 June 2016}}</ref> The ''Save Malaysia Stop Lynas'' (SMSL) group is currently led by [[Bentong]] [[Malaysian general election, 2013|parliamentary candidate]] Wong Tack.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.themalaysianinsider.com/malaysia/article/kuantan-city-folk-to-lead-anti-lynas-plant-movement/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-08-07 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120604115607/http://www.themalaysianinsider.com/malaysia/article/kuantan-city-folk-to-lead-anti-lynas-plant-movement/ |archivedate=2012-06-04 |df= }}</ref>

The refining facility entered production in 2013, producing 1,089 tonnes of rare earth oxides in the first quarter of 2014, with a target of 11,000 tonnes per annum.<ref>{{cite news | title=Lynas soars on record production | author=Elizabeth Redman | date=2014-04-01 | publisher=Business Spectator | url=http://www.businessspectator.com.au/news/2014/4/1/resources-and-energy/lynas-soars-record-production}}</ref> On 2 September 2014, Lynas was issued a 2-year Full Operating Stage License (FOSL) by the Malaysian [[Prime Minister's Department|Atomic Energy Licensing Board]] (AELB).<ref name="MI 20140902"/>

