{{short description|Quarrying term for any hard dark-coloured rock}}
{{refimprove|date=December 2011}}

'''Whinstone''' is a term used in the [[quarry]]ing industry to describe any hard dark-coloured [[Rock (geology)|rock]]. Examples include the [[igneous rock]]s, [[basalt]] and [[dolerite]], as well as the [[sedimentary rock]], [[chert]].<ref>[http://thesaurus.english-heritage.org.uk/thesaurus_term.asp?thes_no=129&term_no=98293 English Heritage Online Thesaurus]</ref><ref>[http://www.thefreedictionary.com/whinstone ''The American Heritage Dictionary of the English Language'', 4th edition (2000), Houghton Mifflin]</ref>

==Description==
Massive outcrops of whinstone occur include the [[Pentland Hills]], Scotland and the [[Whin Sill]]s, England.<ref>[http://thesaurus.english-heritage.org.uk/thesaurus_term.asp?thes_no=129&term_no=98293 English Heritage Online Thesaurus]</ref> 

The name 'whin' derives from the sound it makes when struck with a hammer<ref>[http://thesaurus.english-heritage.org.uk/thesaurus_term.asp?thes_no=129&term_no=98293 English Heritage Online Thesaurus]</ref>. It is used for road chippings and [[dry stone wall]]s, but its natural angular shapes do not fit together well and are not easy to build with, and its hardness makes it a difficult material to work<ref>[http://thesaurus.english-heritage.org.uk/thesaurus_term.asp?thes_no=129&term_no=98293 English Heritage Online Thesaurus]</ref>. A common use is in the laying of patios and driveways in its ground/by product state called [[Whindust]].<ref>[http://thesaurus.english-heritage.org.uk/thesaurus_term.asp?thes_no=129&term_no=98293 English Heritage Online Thesaurus]</ref>

